      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texas’s political status was complex; it was governed as part of Coahuila y Tejas under Mexico’s federal system, which later shifted toward centralism, causing friction with settlers.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from en.wikipedia.org; tshaonline.org; dp.la. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texas was not an independent territory but part of a Mexican state</li><li>Governed under Mexican federalist constitution initially</li><li>Political power centralized in Mexican government over time</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Discuss how changes from federalism to centralism in Mexico affected Texas governance.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Explain how political centralization might cause unrest in a distant region like Texas.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming Texas had self-governance similar to a U.S. state at the time.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> en.wikipedia.org; tshaonline.org; dp.la <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p>"
