    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">07</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Early Conflict</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">The Battle of Gonzales: First Armed Clash</h2><ul><li>October 1835: Settlers resisted Mexican troops attempting to seize a cannon</li><li>Known as the 'Come and Take It' battle</li><li>Marked the start of open rebellion</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The Battle of Gonzales was the first military engagement of the Texas Revolution, symbolizing settler defiance against Mexican authority. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Analyze how a small conflict over a cannon escalated into a broader war.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Why might a symbolic event like this galvanize a larger movement?</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Underestimating the significance of early skirmishes in revolutionary movements.</p></div></div>",
