    "num": "10",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">10</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Declaration of Independence</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texas Declares Independence: March 2, 1836</h2><ul><li>Convention at Washington-on-the-Brazos adopted the Texas Declaration</li><li>Outlined grievances against Mexican government</li><li>Established the Republic of Texas</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">On March 2, 1836, Texas formally declared independence, citing violations of rights and governance failures by Mexico. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s5\">[5]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s13\">[13]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Review key grievances listed in the Texas Declaration of Independence.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify reasons Texans gave for seeking independence.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming the declaration was spontaneous rather than a formal political process.</p></div><div id=\"quiz-slide10\" class=\"quizbox popquiz anim\" data-quiz=\"[{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;mc&quot;,&quot;level&quot;:2,&quot;q&quot;:&quot;Which of the following best describes the political status of Texas before the revolution?&quot;,&quot;options&quot;:[&quot;A Mexican state within the province of Coahuila y Tejas&quot;,&quot;An independent republic allied with the United States&quot;,&quot;A U.S. territory under federal control&quot;,&quot;A Spanish colony governed directly from Madrid&quot;],&quot;answer&quot;:0,&quot;why&quot;:&quot;Texas was part of the Mexican state of Coahuila y Tejas before declaring independence.&quot;},{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;sa&quot;,&quot;level&quot;:3,&quot;q&quot;:&quot;Describe the significance of the Texas War of Independence in American history.&quot;,&quot;rubric&quot;:&quot;Response should include the impact on U.S. territorial expansion, the establishment of the Republic of Texas, and the conflict&#39;s role in U.S.-Mexico relations.&quot;,&quot;sample&quot;:&quot;The Texas War of Independence was significant because it led to the creation of the Republic of Texas, which later joined the United States, contributing to U.S. territorial expansion and increasing tensions with Mexico that eventually led to the Mexican-American War.&quot;,&quot;accept&quot;:[&quot;It led to Texas becoming an independent republic and later a U.S. state, influencing American expansion.&quot;,&quot;The war marked a key conflict that shaped U.S.-Mexico relations and territorial boundaries.&quot;,&quot;It was important for American history because it contributed to the idea of Manifest Destiny and westward expansion.&quot;]}]\" data-pop=\"1\"></div></div>",
