      "h": "Building a New Nation: The Republic of Texas",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Following independence, Texas formed a republic with its own constitution and leadership, laying the foundation for self-governance.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from history.com; dp.la; tsl.texas.gov. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Adopted a constitution modeled on U.S. principles</li><li>Sam Houston elected as first president</li><li>Set up government institutions and military</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Compare the Texas Constitution with the U.S. Constitution in structure and rights.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Discuss challenges in creating a new government after revolution.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming immediate stability after independence without transitional challenges.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> history.com; dp.la; tsl.texas.gov <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s5\">[5]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s14\">[14]</sup></p>"
